These data provide overwhelming evidence that the probability of survival is associated with the physical characteristics of the birds (Drop-in-Deviance Test, p-value < 0.00001). The physical characteristics of the birds that are most associated with the probability of survival are the total length from the tip of the beak to the tip of the tail in millimeters (p-value < 0.00001), weight in grams (p-value = 0.011), length of humerus in inches (p-value < 0.001), and the length of the keel of the sternum in inches (p-value = 0.020).


Basic 20.16_3rd Excellent work. You used a backward selection procedure to arrive at 4 key variables. If you check the VIFs, you’ll find that with the full set of variables, many of the variables had VIFs greater than 4 indicating problems with multicollinearity. There are a variety of solutions that have been proposed: PC regression, Ridge regression, lasso, but the latest is to use Bayesian model averaging with Bayesian Information Content BIC as a criterion. I’ll present that tonight, and you end up with the same 4 variables that you found: TL + WT + HL + KL Score 5/5

#read in the data
HIV <- Sleuth3::ex2118

#take a look at the dataset
head(HIV)
##    Contact Circumcised HIV Number NoHIV
## 1   Single         Yes   1     46    45
## 2   Single          No   5     27    22
## 3 Multiple         Yes   5    168   163
## 4 Multiple          No  13     52    39
#create variables of interest 
Response1 <- cbind(ex2118$HIV, ex2118$Number-ex2118$HIV)
Circ <- ifelse(ex2118$Circumcised == "No", 1, 0)
Contact_S <- ifelse(ex2118$Contact == "Multiple", 1, 0)

#run glm 
HIV_glm <- glm(Response1 ~ Circ + Contact_S, family = binomial)

#get the odds ratio from the glm summary and back transform the odds ratio
summary(HIV_glm)

Supplemental 20.20_3rd Excellent answer! Harrell (2015, 2021) argues that you shouldn’t automatically drop explanatory variables just because the p value is greater than 0.05. You dropped gender, but you could have presented it too. Females have 14% higher self esteem than males (1-exp(-.146214)), but the 95% CI includes 1. Score 2.5/2.5
